## ORM
Use `@api.multi` for recordsets and `@api.model` for model-level methods.
Avoid `@api.one`. Call `ensure_one()` when a single record is required.
Use parameterized SQL only. Batch `write()` and `unlink()` operations.
Document every `sudo()` with a short reason.
Prefer ORM over SQL. If SQL writes are unavoidable, invalidate or refresh affected caches.

## Performance
Avoid `search()` or `browse(id)` inside loops.
Prefer `read_group(..., lazy=False)` for grouped counts and sums.
Push filtering into domains when possible.
Use `search_count()` instead of `len(search())`.
Batch recordset work with `mapped`, `filtered`, grouped domains, and set operations.
Keep computed fields prefetch-friendly; declare complete `@api.depends`.
Store computed fields only when they are searched, grouped, sorted, or repeatedly displayed at scale.

## Views and models
Use standard Odoo 12 xpath positions and attrs dictionaries.
Keep model methods small and focused.
Declare complete `@api.depends`.
Use `_sql_constraints` or `@api.constrains` for validation.
Keep XML IDs stable and verify manifest data order when adding views, security, or data files.

## Security and style
Keep `ir.model.access` and `ir.rule` aligned with new models.
Raise `UserError` for business rules and `ValidationError` for bad data.
Use `_logger`, not `print()`.
Keep imports ordered: stdlib, third-party, odoo, local.
Respect multi-company and record rules unless the task explicitly requires privileged behavior.

## Verification
Prefer the narrowest module-level check available.
For install/update verification, use the project venv and run `-u <module> --stop-after-init` against the relevant database when safe.
